Adaptive Cryptographic State Machines: A Formal Framework for Quantum‑Safe Decentralized Ledgers


Author: Ouadi Maakoul

Second Edition 


---


Abstract


The imminent arrival of cryptographically relevant quantum computers (CRQCs) threatens all deployed blockchains that rely on the elliptic curve discrete logarithm problem (ECDLP) over secp256k1. Recent circuit optimizations (Google Quantum AI, 2026) demonstrate that a CRQC with as few as 1200 logical qubits can solve secp256k1 ECDLP in under 23 minutes—approximately 9 minutes in an on‑spend primed attack, comparable to Bitcoin’s block interval. Despite this, decentralized ledgers exhibit a critical adaptation gap: the coordination time T_C required to upgrade cryptographic primitives (12–20 months) may exceed the remaining time until quantum break. We formalize this gap via a threshold public goods game and prove an Adaptation Gap Theorem: under rational validator behavior, the probability of successful voluntary pre‑quantum migration decays exponentially as \exp(-\Omega(N(1-\theta)^2)), rendering it negligible for large validator sets.


To solve the adaptation gap, we transition from voluntary coordination to systemic enforcement via the Adaptive Cryptographic State Machine (ACSM). The ACSM implements three mathematically proven pillars:


1. Protocol‑Level Forcing Function: A degrading reward coefficient \phi(t) is derived directly from the public distribution of quantum arrival times. We prove that for t > t^*, the strategy upgrade becomes strictly dominant for all validators with reasonable costs, collapsing the N-player coordination game into independent rational choices.

2. Hybrid Commitment State: A mandatory composite address \alpha = H_{512}\big(H_{512}(\mathsf{pk}_\text{EC}) \,\|\, H_{512}(\mathsf{pk}_\text{PQC}) \,\|\, \mathsf{salt}\big) supports existential unforgeability: breaking both classical and post‑quantum primitives is necessary to forge a transition after the upgrade epoch.

3. Zero‑Knowledge Key Migration: A NIZK proof of knowledge of the original ECDSA secret key binds a dark account to a new post‑quantum public key without revealing \mathsf{pk}_\text{old}. A nullifier \mathsf{nf} = H_{256}(\mathsf{sk}_\text{old} \,\|\, \mathsf{addr}_\text{old}) prevents double migration, and quantum soundness is proven under lattice assumptions. Moreover, migration proofs can be recursively aggregated, reducing per‑account cost to negligible levels.


We further provide a recursive SNARK aggregation lemma showing that the 33\times signature size increase can be amortized to constant verification time, ensuring liveness. The ACSM is proved safe (\Pr[\text{inconsistent state}] \leq 2^{-128}) and live (O(\text{block time} \cdot \log N)) under honest majority, with explicit consideration of validator exit. A Bitcoin‑compatible variant is presented via a soft‑fork timelock. All results are purely mathematical; no empirical simulations are included.


