1.6 Related Work


Our work builds on several threads: Shor’s algorithm optimizations for ECDLP (Gidney & Ekerå, 2021; Google Quantum AI, 2026); NIST post‑quantum standards (FIPS 203–206); QROM security reductions (Albrecht et al., 2022; Don et al., 2022); coordination game analyses of blockchain upgrades (Barrera & Hurder, 2024); and cryptographic agility proposals (Boneh et al., 2023). The forcing function draws inspiration from Ethereum’s inactivity leak and from economic penalty mechanisms in proof‑of‑stake systems. The hybrid address concept extends discussions on hash‑committed accounts (Ethereum Community, 2026). The ZK migration approach parallels privacy‑preserving nullifier systems (Semaphore, Zenrock Hush) but adapts them to post‑quantum assumptions. Recursive SNARK aggregation for PQC signatures is conjectured to be possible via lattice‑based folding schemes (LatticeFold, Boneh & Chen, 2025), though full IVC remains an active research area.


1.7 Scope and Limitations


This work is theoretical. We do not provide implementation code, empirical benchmarks, or simulations. We assume standard cryptographic hardness assumptions (ECDLP, MLWE, SIS, collision resistance of SHA‑3‑512). We assume an honest majority (>2/3 stake) for consensus safety and liveness. The forcing function parameters are derived from public expert elicitation on \tau_Q; we do not model optimal parameter selection in a strategic sense. The recursive SNARK aggregation lemma assumes the existence of a post‑quantum IVC scheme (e.g., a lattice‑based folding scheme extended to full IVC) and does not prove its security from first principles. Despite these limitations, the formal framework provides a rigorous foundation for future implementation, simulation, and standardization efforts.


