A.1 Elliptic Curve Cryptography


Definition A.1 (Elliptic curve over finite field). Let \mathbb{F}_p be a finite field with prime p > 3. An elliptic curve E over \mathbb{F}_p is defined by the Weierstrass equation


E: y^2 = x^3 + ax + b, \quad a,b \in \mathbb{F}_p,\ 4a^3 + 27b^2 \neq 0.


The set E(\mathbb{F}_p) consists of all points (x,y) \in \mathbb{F}_p^2 satisfying the equation together with a point at infinity \mathcal{O}. This set forms an abelian group under the chord‑tangent law.


Definition A.2 (secp256k1). The curve secp256k1 is defined by a = 0, b = 7 over the prime field


p = 2^{256} - 2^{32} - 977.


Its group order is the prime


n = 115792089237316195423570985008687907852837564279074904382605163141518161494337.


A.2 Hash Functions


We use SHA‑3‑512, denoted H. Its 256‑bit truncation is denoted H_{256}.


Definition A.3 (Collision resistance). A hash function H: \{0,1\}^* \to \{0,1\}^\ell is collision‑resistant if for any QPT adversary \mathcal{A},


\Pr[(x,y) \leftarrow \mathcal{A}(1^\lambda) : x \neq y,\ H(x)=H(y)] \leq \text{negl}(\lambda).


Definition A.4 (Quantum collision resistance). For a hash function with output length \ell, the best quantum collision attack (Brassard–Høyer–Tapp) requires O(2^{\ell/3}) queries. For \ell = 512, this is \approx 2^{170}, exceeding the 2^{128} security target.


A.3 Digital Signatures


Definition A.5 (EUF‑CMA security). A signature scheme \Sigma = (\text{KeyGen}, \text{Sign}, \text{Verify}) is existentially unforgeable under chosen message attacks if for any QPT adversary \mathcal{A} with access to a signing oracle \text{Sign}(sk, \cdot),


\Pr\left[ \begin{array}{l}

(pk,sk) \leftarrow \text{KeyGen}(1^\lambda),\\

(m^*, \sigma^*) \leftarrow \mathcal{A}^{\text{Sign}(sk,\cdot)}(pk) :\\

\text{Verify}(pk, m^*, \sigma^*) = 1 \land m^* \notin Q

\end{array} \right] \leq \text{negl}(\lambda),


where Q is the set of messages queried to the signing oracle.


